WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.636 --> 00:00:03.386
(relaxing music)

2
00:00:08.566 --> 00:00:09.399 line:15% 
<v Presenter>Well, we're gonna start</v>

3
00:00:09.399 --> 00:00:10.290 line:15% 
with peripheral vascular disease,

4
00:00:10.290 --> 00:00:13.170 line:15% 
a very important topic, not only for the board exam,

5
00:00:13.170 --> 00:00:15.330 line:15% 
but definitely for your patients.

6
00:00:15.330 --> 00:00:19.320 line:15% 
And to do that, we're joined by Dr. Robert Dachs.

7
00:00:19.320 --> 00:00:21.708 line:15% 
Bob is the Director of Graduate Medical Education

8
00:00:21.708 --> 00:00:25.500 line:15% 
and part of the Department of Emergency Medicine

9
00:00:25.500 --> 00:00:28.440 line:15% 
at Ellis Hospital in Schenectady, New York.

10
00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:30.480 line:15% 
He is also a clinical associate professor

11
00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:32.790 line:15% 
in the Department of Family Medicine

12
00:00:32.790 --> 00:00:34.830 line:15% 
and works with the family medicine residents.

13
00:00:34.830 --> 00:00:38.760 line:15% 
He is a board certified family physician himself,

14
00:00:38.760 --> 00:00:42.810 line:15% 
part of Albany Medical College in Albany, New York.

15
00:00:42.810 --> 00:00:45.870 line:15% 
<v ->It's great to be here and to do the course once again.</v>

16
00:00:45.870 --> 00:00:48.390 line:15% 
So peripheral vascular disease, yes,

17
00:00:48.390 --> 00:00:49.830 line:15% 
there's usually two or three questions

18
00:00:49.830 --> 00:00:51.630 line:15% 
you'll have on the boards of peripheral vascular disease.

19
00:00:51.630 --> 00:00:54.599 line:15% 
I hope to cover what might show up for you.

20
00:00:54.599 --> 00:00:55.432 line:15% 
Got nothing to disclose.

21
00:00:55.432 --> 00:00:56.850
Here's my learning objectives

22
00:00:56.850 --> 00:00:59.220
and when I do peripheralvascular disease lecture,

23
00:00:59.220 --> 00:01:00.480
I like to begin at the beginning.

24
00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:03.060
Let's start with the aorta and work our way down.

25
00:01:03.060 --> 00:01:04.944
So we talk about two aortic diseases,

26
00:01:04.944 --> 00:01:08.520
aortic dissection and abdominal aortic aneurysm.

27
00:01:08.520 --> 00:01:11.100
Let's do the one you're gonna possibly see more of,

28
00:01:11.100 --> 00:01:15.150
which is the bottom one, AAA, abdominal aortic aneurysm.

29
00:01:15.150 --> 00:01:15.990
But even before we get there

30
00:01:15.990 --> 00:01:17.640
and we start talking about aneurysms,

31
00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:18.630
it's always good to know,

32
00:01:18.630 --> 00:01:21.090
what's the definition of an aneurysm?

33
00:01:21.090 --> 00:01:25.290
So the aneurysm is when the vessel diameter is greater

34
00:01:25.290 --> 00:01:27.630
than 50%, it's normal size.

35
00:01:27.630 --> 00:01:30.180
So a typical abdominal aorta

36
00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:33.600
is approximately two centimeters in diameter.

37
00:01:33.600 --> 00:01:38.220
So when it gets to three centimeters, you have an aneurysm.

38
00:01:38.220 --> 00:01:39.330
How common is it?

39
00:01:39.330 --> 00:01:40.920
It's very common.

40
00:01:40.920 --> 00:01:42.706
2% to 5% of the elderly population

41
00:01:42.706 --> 00:01:45.960
harbor a abdominal aortic aneurysm.

42
00:01:45.960 --> 00:01:48.090
Completely asymptomatic, it's just there,

43
00:01:48.090 --> 00:01:49.920
doesn't bother them.

44
00:01:49.920 --> 00:01:53.250
But it won't bother them until it typically ruptures.

45
00:01:53.250 --> 00:01:55.380
And it's the 14th most common cause of death

46
00:01:55.380 --> 00:01:57.210
in the United States.

47
00:01:57.210 --> 00:02:00.210
What causes AAAs?

48
00:02:00.210 --> 00:02:03.180
Atherosclerosis, too many Big Mac attacks.

49
00:02:03.180 --> 00:02:04.500
And in particular smoking,

50
00:02:04.500 --> 00:02:09.500
smoking is really associated with developing a AAA.

51
00:02:09.540 --> 00:02:10.740
Where are they located?

52
00:02:10.740 --> 00:02:14.640
95% of them are below the takeoff

53
00:02:14.640 --> 00:02:16.860
of the renal arteries or infrarenal

54
00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:19.590
and there's, more men than women have it.

55
00:02:19.590 --> 00:02:21.450
As I mentioned, they're asymptomatic

56
00:02:21.450 --> 00:02:22.470
until they go,

57
00:02:22.470 --> 00:02:23.303
(Dr. Dachs vocalizing)

58
00:02:23.303 --> 00:02:24.136
until they rupture.

59
00:02:24.136 --> 00:02:26.670
And once they rupture or leak,

60
00:02:26.670 --> 00:02:28.560
60% to 80% of those people die

61
00:02:28.560 --> 00:02:30.720
before they make it into my ER doors.

62
00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:32.430
Of those who make it into the ER doors,

63
00:02:32.430 --> 00:02:34.710
50% of them don't leave the hospital alive.

64
00:02:34.710 --> 00:02:39.690
So incredibly high mortality associated with a ruptured AAA.

65
00:02:39.690 --> 00:02:43.260
Therefore you want to prevent that, that's what we do.

66
00:02:43.260 --> 00:02:45.510
Alright, so "Because of the prevalence and it's lethality,

67
00:02:45.510 --> 00:02:49.770
the USPSTF recommends ultrasound screening

68
00:02:49.770 --> 00:02:51.540
be performed on which patients?"

69
00:02:51.540 --> 00:02:53.970
Okay, because of its prevalence and lethality,

70
00:02:53.970 --> 00:02:55.263
the rupture of AAA.

71
00:02:56.400 --> 00:02:59.400
Does USPTF say, "A, we recommend a one-time screening

72
00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:02.550
for men ages 65 to 75 who have ever smoked.

73
00:03:02.550 --> 00:03:04.980
Onetime screening for men 65 to 75,

74
00:03:04.980 --> 00:03:06.780
regardless of their smoking history.

75
00:03:07.710 --> 00:03:09.540
C, onetime screening for both men and women,

76
00:03:09.540 --> 00:03:11.970
ages 65 to 75 who have ever smoked

77
00:03:11.970 --> 00:03:13.950
and D, onetime screening for both men and women,

78
00:03:13.950 --> 00:03:16.917
ages 65 to 75, regardless of their smoking history."

79
00:03:22.620 --> 00:03:24.540
Because you know this, it's one time screening

80
00:03:24.540 --> 00:03:26.610
for men who have ever smoked.

81
00:03:26.610 --> 00:03:27.660
Definition of ever smoked

82
00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:29.553
is 100 cigarettes in your lifetime.

83
00:03:30.780 --> 00:03:33.900
Now here is your take home slide,

84
00:03:33.900 --> 00:03:36.150
David likes to say take these slides home,

85
00:03:36.150 --> 00:03:38.670
this is one of them, it just says what I just said,

86
00:03:38.670 --> 00:03:41.160
there's a B recommendation for the men.

87
00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:43.470
As for the men who have never smoked,

88
00:03:43.470 --> 00:03:46.440
don't know, it's a C, you can consider it.

89
00:03:46.440 --> 00:03:48.960
There's too little evidence in women who have ever smoked

90
00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:53.160
and a D for women who have never smoked, don't go there!

91
00:03:53.160 --> 00:03:54.000
Just don't go there.

92
00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:58.680
Now, not being a sexist on this.

93
00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:01.590
I always put these sort of slides in, not for you to study,

94
00:04:01.590 --> 00:04:04.560
but just to back up what I say.

95
00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:06.930
So when you see some of my slides

96
00:04:06.930 --> 00:04:10.470
that may mention this trial, that trial, this trial,

97
00:04:10.470 --> 00:04:11.880
don't memorize the trials.

98
00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:14.820
They're not gonna ask you the name of the trial,

99
00:04:14.820 --> 00:04:16.350
just the take home message

100
00:04:16.350 --> 00:04:18.420
and the take home message on this Chichester Trial

101
00:04:18.420 --> 00:04:19.290
that was done in England

102
00:04:19.290 --> 00:04:21.750
took all these women over 65,

103
00:04:21.750 --> 00:04:25.757
randomly assigned them the screening versus nothing

104
00:04:25.757 --> 00:04:28.440
and it made no difference, it made no difference.

105
00:04:28.440 --> 00:04:29.970
So don't go screening women,

106
00:04:29.970 --> 00:04:33.690
particularly ones who have never smoked for a AAA screen.

107
00:04:33.690 --> 00:04:38.690
Now there is one caveat, this is not what the USPSTF says,

108
00:04:39.300 --> 00:04:41.970
but what our government allows.

109
00:04:41.970 --> 00:04:46.890
So Medicare part B does allow for men

110
00:04:46.890 --> 00:04:49.320
who have ever smoked, aged 65 to 75

111
00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:53.640
or men or women regardless of their smoking history

112
00:04:53.640 --> 00:04:56.941
if they have a first degree relative who's had a AAA,

113
00:04:56.941 --> 00:05:00.810
they will pay for a AAA screen.

114
00:05:00.810 --> 00:05:02.100
So that's what Medicare says,

115
00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:05.280
which is different than what USPTSF tests says.

116
00:05:05.280 --> 00:05:06.870
So just understand the difference,

117
00:05:06.870 --> 00:05:09.870
'cause in practice you may be doing what Medicare tells you,

118
00:05:09.870 --> 00:05:12.483
understand what the academics are from USPSTF.

119
00:05:14.072 --> 00:05:19.072
Next question, you happen to have found AAA on that screen,

120
00:05:19.620 --> 00:05:21.600
'cause you had a male who smoked.

121
00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:23.245
At what size should you refer them

122
00:05:23.245 --> 00:05:25.470
for surgical intervention?

123
00:05:25.470 --> 00:05:27.690
When should you send them out to the vascular surgeons

124
00:05:27.690 --> 00:05:29.466
or your interventional radiologist?

125
00:05:29.466 --> 00:05:31.530
Is it when it's three to three and a half centimeters,

126
00:05:31.530 --> 00:05:32.550
four to four and a half centimeters,

127
00:05:32.550 --> 00:05:33.450
five, five and a half centimeters,

128
00:05:33.450 --> 00:05:35.150
Six or six and a half centimeters?

129
00:05:40.350 --> 00:05:41.580
Good, most of you know this one,

130
00:05:41.580 --> 00:05:42.660
it's five to five and a half.

131
00:05:42.660 --> 00:05:45.600
They've asked this question in the past, so just be aware.

132
00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:46.433
Will it come up again?

133
00:05:46.433 --> 00:05:49.863
I don't know, but it is five to five and a half centimeters.

134
00:05:50.877 --> 00:05:52.590
And here's why.

135
00:05:52.590 --> 00:05:55.860
Up to five, five and a half centimeters, there's no issue,

136
00:05:55.860 --> 00:05:57.480
it doesn't rupture,

137
00:05:57.480 --> 00:05:59.310
for the most part, there's not a problem.

138
00:05:59.310 --> 00:06:00.960
Once it hits five, five centimeters,

139
00:06:00.960 --> 00:06:02.610
then that aneurysm starts to grow

140
00:06:02.610 --> 00:06:04.964
bigger, faster, quicker, and

141
00:06:04.964 --> 00:06:06.030
(Dr. Dachs vocalizing)

142
00:06:06.030 --> 00:06:07.053
then may go.

143
00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:10.050
So the rate of increase is exponential.

144
00:06:10.050 --> 00:06:12.780
The larger the diameter, the aneurysm,

145
00:06:12.780 --> 00:06:14.980
the faster it's gonna get bigger and bigger.

146
00:06:15.920 --> 00:06:19.800
So the question is, you've got an ultrasound report

147
00:06:19.800 --> 00:06:23.010
that says X amount of centimeters in diameter.

148
00:06:23.010 --> 00:06:26.580
How frequently should you be repeating that ultrasound

149
00:06:26.580 --> 00:06:28.170
to follow it?

150
00:06:28.170 --> 00:06:29.640
This is one of the recommendations

151
00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:32.340
from the vascular surgeons who say, listen,

152
00:06:32.340 --> 00:06:34.050
those small ones,

153
00:06:34.050 --> 00:06:36.421
you get a report three and a half centimeters.

154
00:06:36.421 --> 00:06:37.980
When's the next time

155
00:06:37.980 --> 00:06:39.630
you should actually look at that again?

156
00:06:39.630 --> 00:06:41.250
In like three years,

157
00:06:41.250 --> 00:06:45.420
'cause the small ones grow very, very, very slowly.

158
00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:46.950
If they're bigger and bigger and bigger,

159
00:06:46.950 --> 00:06:48.273
you go more frequently.

160
00:06:50.411 --> 00:06:53.160
Let's move upstream back to dissection,

161
00:06:53.160 --> 00:06:54.630
up here in the chest.

162
00:06:54.630 --> 00:06:57.180
So dissections, who gets them?

163
00:06:57.180 --> 00:06:58.410
Men more than women.

164
00:06:58.410 --> 00:07:02.220
Hypertension is the leading cause of a dissection.

165
00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:06.360
There are other causes, cardiac surgery, Marfans

166
00:07:06.360 --> 00:07:08.520
or other connective tissue diseases,

167
00:07:08.520 --> 00:07:10.920
cocaine use in the peripartum region.

168
00:07:10.920 --> 00:07:13.740
Now I'm gonna make one mention about Marfans.

169
00:07:13.740 --> 00:07:15.780
There was one question once on inservice,

170
00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:18.213
so I threw in one slide on Marfans.

171
00:07:19.110 --> 00:07:22.106
Everybody thinks Marfans, everybody thinks Abraham Lincoln,

172
00:07:22.106 --> 00:07:26.400
but there's other signs and symptoms of Marfans

173
00:07:26.400 --> 00:07:27.240
or I should say signs,

174
00:07:27.240 --> 00:07:31.080
not say symptoms, sternal abnormalities,

175
00:07:31.080 --> 00:07:33.900
such as those things, abnormal joint flexibility.

176
00:07:33.900 --> 00:07:36.450
One of these I like to point out is the Steinberg Sign,

177
00:07:36.450 --> 00:07:37.920
that's where you take your thumb,

178
00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:39.750
put it in the palm of your hand

179
00:07:39.750 --> 00:07:41.670
and you wrap your fingers around it

180
00:07:41.670 --> 00:07:44.430
and if you have abnormal flexibility,

181
00:07:44.430 --> 00:07:47.177
you'll see your thumb come out past the hypothenar eminence.

182
00:07:47.177 --> 00:07:49.530
So you go like that.

183
00:07:49.530 --> 00:07:51.300
Yeah, I see a couple of you people doing this.

184
00:07:51.300 --> 00:07:53.423
Yeah, you doing this?
(audience laughing)

185
00:07:53.423 --> 00:07:57.246
I see a couple people just said holy crap, I can do that!

186
00:07:57.246 --> 00:07:59.520
(all laughing)

187
00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:01.860
Don't freak, it's only one sign.

188
00:08:01.860 --> 00:08:06.860
And actually if you go to the Marfan Syndrome website,

189
00:08:07.950 --> 00:08:09.660
there's actually a scoring system

190
00:08:09.660 --> 00:08:11.340
that if you get more than seven points,

191
00:08:11.340 --> 00:08:14.643
that's who you should refer for genetic testing.

192
00:08:17.686 --> 00:08:19.140
I'd like to go back

193
00:08:19.140 --> 00:08:21.690
and just mention one thing about dissection and AAA,

194
00:08:21.690 --> 00:08:24.686
they're not the same thing.

195
00:08:24.686 --> 00:08:26.550
The pathophysiology is different.

196
00:08:26.550 --> 00:08:30.210
This is my artist's rendition of a AAA.

197
00:08:30.210 --> 00:08:31.980
You see a true aneurysm,

198
00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:36.450
all three layers of the vessel wall will dilate out,

199
00:08:36.450 --> 00:08:39.660
intima, media and adventitia, the whole thing goes out.

200
00:08:39.660 --> 00:08:42.600
What happens in a dissection, up here in your chest,

201
00:08:42.600 --> 00:08:46.230
is after that hypertension, longstanding hypertension,

202
00:08:46.230 --> 00:08:48.270
you'll get an intimal tear.

203
00:08:48.270 --> 00:08:49.770
And with that intimal tear,

204
00:08:49.770 --> 00:08:53.100
you'll now create a second lumen inside the media.

205
00:08:53.100 --> 00:08:57.104
It becomes a two lumen problem is what a dissection is.

206
00:08:57.104 --> 00:08:59.880
And there's two types of dissections,

207
00:08:59.880 --> 00:09:03.060
there's the ascending, type A, descending, type B.

208
00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:06.363
That's easy, make it easy on yourself, A is ascending.

209
00:09:07.852 --> 00:09:09.450
How do these people present?

210
00:09:09.450 --> 00:09:10.283
How do patients present?

211
00:09:10.283 --> 00:09:11.160
I think everybody learned

212
00:09:11.160 --> 00:09:13.650
like in the first week of med school, dissection,

213
00:09:13.650 --> 00:09:16.590
oh, that's a tearing ripping interscapular pain,

214
00:09:16.590 --> 00:09:17.940
everybody learned that?

215
00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:19.600
Well, actually it's interesting,

216
00:09:19.600 --> 00:09:22.563
more commonly it's anterior chest pain.

217
00:09:23.730 --> 00:09:25.290
Anterior chest pain, well think about it.

218
00:09:25.290 --> 00:09:28.560
Two thirds of dissections are type A

219
00:09:28.560 --> 00:09:31.500
from the ascending aorta.

220
00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:33.960
Where is your ascending aorta?

221
00:09:33.960 --> 00:09:35.880
It's an anterior structure,

222
00:09:35.880 --> 00:09:37.890
so they have anterior chest pain.

223
00:09:37.890 --> 00:09:40.500
As the dissection moves along,

224
00:09:40.500 --> 00:09:45.240
it may then involve your descending thoracic aorta.

225
00:09:45.240 --> 00:09:48.180
But it starts more commonly, the type As,

226
00:09:48.180 --> 00:09:50.133
with anterior chest pain.

227
00:09:51.240 --> 00:09:54.450
How do you make the diagnosis of a dissection?

228
00:09:54.450 --> 00:09:56.460
Any way you can.
(Dr. Dachs laughing)

229
00:09:56.460 --> 00:09:57.840
Any way you can.

230
00:09:57.840 --> 00:10:00.510
Most commonly, well, in the ER now,

231
00:10:00.510 --> 00:10:05.510
the quickest, easiest to do is a CTA a CT angiography,

232
00:10:05.730 --> 00:10:07.080
that's what I show you here

233
00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:08.160
and I don't know if you can see it,

234
00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:11.160
but I put the arrows there, you can see two lumens.

235
00:10:11.160 --> 00:10:15.180
You see two lumens, there's two lumens here

236
00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:16.710
and that's how you make the diagnosis.

237
00:10:16.710 --> 00:10:18.570
If you make the diagnosis, what do you wanna do?

238
00:10:18.570 --> 00:10:20.370
You actually wanna lower the blood pressure,

239
00:10:20.370 --> 00:10:23.343
you wanna stop this thing from progressing on further.

240
00:10:25.470 --> 00:10:27.690
Now we are gonna work our way downstream

241
00:10:27.690 --> 00:10:29.250
and talk about the more common things

242
00:10:29.250 --> 00:10:31.320
you'll see potentially in your office practice.

243
00:10:31.320 --> 00:10:33.960
That's peripheral vascular disease

244
00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:35.730
that presents with claudication,

245
00:10:35.730 --> 00:10:37.830
classically in the lower extremities

246
00:10:37.830 --> 00:10:42.450
or an acute thromboembolic problem

247
00:10:42.450 --> 00:10:44.940
that will present with The 5 "P's."

248
00:10:44.940 --> 00:10:46.740
Let's do the thing that shows up in your office,

249
00:10:46.740 --> 00:10:49.117
which is a claudication.

250
00:10:50.827 --> 00:10:53.520
This is really, I like to put this definition,

251
00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:56.340
because it just explains everything.

252
00:10:56.340 --> 00:10:58.057
Claudication is right there,

253
00:10:58.057 --> 00:11:00.000
"Reproducible ischemic muscle pain

254
00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.100
that occurs with exercise, relieved with rest."

255
00:11:02.100 --> 00:11:05.490
In other words, it's stable angina of the legs.

256
00:11:05.490 --> 00:11:08.412
So when you have angina, coronary angina,

257
00:11:08.412 --> 00:11:12.270
because you've got a fixed lesion, you exert yourself,

258
00:11:12.270 --> 00:11:14.610
there's not enough supply and demand

259
00:11:14.610 --> 00:11:17.280
and so you get chest pain, you stop,

260
00:11:17.280 --> 00:11:19.830
the pain goes away, that's angina.

261
00:11:19.830 --> 00:11:21.450
Well what happens with claudication?

262
00:11:21.450 --> 00:11:24.210
It's angina of, typically the legs.

263
00:11:24.210 --> 00:11:25.200
You can have the upper extremities,

264
00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:27.000
but you have this fixed lesion

265
00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.730
somewhere in your lower extremity, in your arterial system,

266
00:11:29.730 --> 00:11:32.640
you walk, supply, demand doesn't meet,

267
00:11:32.640 --> 00:11:34.110
your legs start to hurt, what do you do?

268
00:11:34.110 --> 00:11:38.347
You stop, it goes away, that's claudication.

269
00:11:39.390 --> 00:11:41.670
And based on where the pain is,

270
00:11:41.670 --> 00:11:43.832
when the person walks or exerts themselves,

271
00:11:43.832 --> 00:11:47.280
you can guess where the fixed lesion is.

272
00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:50.730
If they get calf symptoms, typically that's fem-pop disease.

273
00:11:50.730 --> 00:11:52.500
If they get calf and thigh disease,

274
00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:54.180
that's probably more common femoral.

275
00:11:54.180 --> 00:11:57.810
And if they get the thigh, hip, buttock pain with impotence,

276
00:11:57.810 --> 00:12:00.060
that's usually aortoiliac disease.

277
00:12:00.060 --> 00:12:03.540
You can always guess where the problem is.

278
00:12:03.540 --> 00:12:05.250
Now your differential diagnosis,

279
00:12:05.250 --> 00:12:09.240
the most common one is spinal stenosis, pseudoclaudication.

280
00:12:09.240 --> 00:12:11.310
usually Dr. Geri mentions a little bit about this

281
00:12:11.310 --> 00:12:12.330
in this back pain talk,

282
00:12:12.330 --> 00:12:14.310
I don't know if he did yesterday or not,

283
00:12:14.310 --> 00:12:17.580
but there you have these other differentials.

284
00:12:17.580 --> 00:12:22.580
The pseudoclaudication spinal stenosis classically presents

285
00:12:22.950 --> 00:12:25.230
in lower extremity pain.

286
00:12:25.230 --> 00:12:28.320
Classically, when a patient walks downhill,

287
00:12:28.320 --> 00:12:30.240
they'll hyperextend their back,

288
00:12:30.240 --> 00:12:32.610
they'll walk and then they'll get some pain in their legs.

289
00:12:32.610 --> 00:12:34.910
The difference is, is the pain will last a while,

290
00:12:34.910 --> 00:12:38.070
the pain will last a while before it settles down,

291
00:12:38.070 --> 00:12:39.390
whereas claudication goes away

292
00:12:39.390 --> 00:12:43.230
very, very quickly, within minutes of stopping.

293
00:12:43.230 --> 00:12:46.190
So here we go, let's do this case.

294
00:12:46.190 --> 00:12:48.630
"A 68-year-old patient presents with complaints

295
00:12:48.630 --> 00:12:50.280
of aching pain in both thighs

296
00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:53.070
when he or she walks about one block.

297
00:12:53.070 --> 00:12:54.930
The pain subsides within one to two minutes

298
00:12:54.930 --> 00:12:56.850
after he or she stops ambulating.

299
00:12:56.850 --> 00:12:58.440
The best initial test in this case,"

300
00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:03.440
'cause your brain is saying that sounds like iliac disease.

301
00:13:03.870 --> 00:13:07.590
So am I gonna perform an ankle-brachial index?

302
00:13:07.590 --> 00:13:09.420
Am I gonna perform bilateral leg ultrasounds?

303
00:13:09.420 --> 00:13:11.130
Am I gonna perform a pulse volume recording

304
00:13:11.130 --> 00:13:14.583
or am I gonna perform an MRA of the lower extremities?

305
00:13:19.650 --> 00:13:22.830
Okay, good, ABI, that's right, that's great.

306
00:13:22.830 --> 00:13:25.620
So how do you do the ABI?

307
00:13:25.620 --> 00:13:28.920
It's fascinating, every time I do this lecture,

308
00:13:28.920 --> 00:13:30.630
I always ask the question, raise of hands.

309
00:13:30.630 --> 00:13:33.000
Everybody knows to do an ABI.

310
00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:34.680
How many of you have the ability

311
00:13:34.680 --> 00:13:36.810
to do an ABI in your office?

312
00:13:36.810 --> 00:13:40.380
There's like a handful, there's like half dozen arms go up.

313
00:13:40.380 --> 00:13:43.544
Most people can't, very easy to do,

314
00:13:43.544 --> 00:13:46.860
you've probably seen it done and it goes like this,

315
00:13:46.860 --> 00:13:49.650
you already have the brachial systolic pressure

316
00:13:49.650 --> 00:13:51.300
when the patient walks into your office.

317
00:13:51.300 --> 00:13:53.370
The nurses did that or your tech did that.

318
00:13:53.370 --> 00:13:55.590
It's written in the chart before you even see the patient.

319
00:13:55.590 --> 00:13:57.750
It's right there, the systolic blood pressure.

320
00:13:57.750 --> 00:14:00.060
How do you go get the ankle one?

321
00:14:00.060 --> 00:14:01.710
Well you just put a blood pressure cuff

322
00:14:01.710 --> 00:14:04.050
around the lower extremity.

323
00:14:04.050 --> 00:14:06.390
Then you take a handheld doppler,

324
00:14:06.390 --> 00:14:09.024
you blow up the blood pressure cuff,

325
00:14:09.024 --> 00:14:09.960
(Dr. Dachs vocalizing)

326
00:14:09.960 --> 00:14:11.280
200 or whatever.

327
00:14:11.280 --> 00:14:14.700
Then you put the doppler over the dorsalis pedis

328
00:14:14.700 --> 00:14:19.320
or the posterior tib, you slowly let down the pressure

329
00:14:19.320 --> 00:14:20.897
in the cuff and then the first,

330
00:14:20.897 --> 00:14:22.290
(Dr. Dachs vocalizing)

331
00:14:22.290 --> 00:14:25.770
at the ankle is a systolic blood pressure at the ankle.

332
00:14:25.770 --> 00:14:30.510
So you and I hopefully have the same blood pressure

333
00:14:30.510 --> 00:14:32.860
here in the arm that we have down in our ankle,

334
00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:38.160
so your ratio should be one, 1.0, near 1.0.

335
00:14:38.160 --> 00:14:43.160
So anything below a ratio of 0.9, below one, is a problem.

336
00:14:45.360 --> 00:14:47.220
So here's how you do it again,

337
00:14:47.220 --> 00:14:50.485
you can see this is how you do it with the picture.

338
00:14:50.485 --> 00:14:52.080
If you do do this in office,

339
00:14:52.080 --> 00:14:54.660
I love making a point on this.

340
00:14:54.660 --> 00:14:57.000
This is in, "American Family Physician."

341
00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.850
The thing that I like to point out about this

342
00:14:59.850 --> 00:15:02.100
is that if you have that handheld doppler,

343
00:15:02.100 --> 00:15:03.780
that's my own personal one on the right,

344
00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:06.540
if you buy these for your office, they're not that crazy,

345
00:15:06.540 --> 00:15:09.510
they're like $450, go get one.

346
00:15:09.510 --> 00:15:11.490
They're good to have, it comes with both probes

347
00:15:11.490 --> 00:15:14.166
and what I'd like to point out when they were doing this,

348
00:15:14.166 --> 00:15:17.910
this one, they used the wrong probe.

349
00:15:17.910 --> 00:15:20.553
The big probe is the OB probe.

350
00:15:21.750 --> 00:15:25.080
You want the little vascular probe when you do this.

351
00:15:25.080 --> 00:15:27.783
So you use the vascular probe, not the OB probe.

352
00:15:28.890 --> 00:15:31.020
Nonetheless, that's how you do it.

353
00:15:31.020 --> 00:15:33.720
And the answer for the boards is normal

354
00:15:33.720 --> 00:15:37.530
is between 0.9 and 1.4, that's normal.

355
00:15:37.530 --> 00:15:41.010
Below 0.9, you have potentially some disease

356
00:15:41.010 --> 00:15:42.310
in your lower extremities.

357
00:15:43.950 --> 00:15:46.470
People often ask me, what if it's above 1.4?

358
00:15:46.470 --> 00:15:48.393
That's potentially a problem also.

359
00:15:49.530 --> 00:15:50.940
What will happen is that you probably have

360
00:15:50.940 --> 00:15:55.260
a very hard, thick, calcified vessel that you can't compress

361
00:15:55.260 --> 00:15:57.120
and that's why you'll get an elevated number.

362
00:15:57.120 --> 00:16:00.753
So the normal number is 0.9 to 1.4 for the boards.

363
00:16:02.369 --> 00:16:04.830
Now let's take another question.

364
00:16:04.830 --> 00:16:07.323
Let's say you are doing ABI.

365
00:16:08.288 --> 00:16:10.050
Remember the American Heart Association,

366
00:16:10.050 --> 00:16:11.760
American College of Cardiology,

367
00:16:11.760 --> 00:16:14.800
recommends when you're obtaining your arm blood pressures,

368
00:16:14.800 --> 00:16:16.628
first of all, they recommend,

369
00:16:16.628 --> 00:16:20.160
I know this happens in very few offices,

370
00:16:20.160 --> 00:16:21.788
I know it doesn't happen

371
00:16:21.788 --> 00:16:23.550
in my primary care doctor's office when I go in,

372
00:16:23.550 --> 00:16:24.570
when the patient comes in,

373
00:16:24.570 --> 00:16:27.187
they should be sitting for five minutes,

374
00:16:27.187 --> 00:16:29.160
both feet on the floor

375
00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:32.550
before the tech comes in and takes the blood pressure.

376
00:16:32.550 --> 00:16:34.140
I'm sure many of your offices don't do it,

377
00:16:34.140 --> 00:16:36.210
like I say, I go and see my primary care doctor,

378
00:16:36.210 --> 00:16:38.760
I come walking in and the first thing and they sit me down,

379
00:16:38.760 --> 00:16:39.840
my feet are up off the thing

380
00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:42.064
and they're taking my blood pressure,

381
00:16:42.064 --> 00:16:43.830
that's not the way you do it.

382
00:16:43.830 --> 00:16:47.940
But if you do it the right way, that's the way you do it,

383
00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:50.790
you then take the higher of the two readings.

384
00:16:50.790 --> 00:16:55.410
Now imagine you have a number that's 140,

385
00:16:55.410 --> 00:16:57.300
let's say you have 140,

386
00:16:57.300 --> 00:17:01.543
but you do it in both arms and one arm is 140

387
00:17:02.727 --> 00:17:06.930
and the other arm systolic is 90.

388
00:17:06.930 --> 00:17:07.763
Let's say there's greater

389
00:17:07.763 --> 00:17:11.673
than 20 millimeters between the arms, huh?

390
00:17:12.570 --> 00:17:15.000
If you have that, what's the most likely diagnosis,

391
00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:17.520
if you have this differential between the two arms?

392
00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:20.250
Is it an acute aortic dissection, chronic aortic aneurysm,

393
00:17:20.250 --> 00:17:23.150
subclavian artery stenosis or a mediastinal mass or tumor?

394
00:17:28.007 --> 00:17:29.970
Yeah, it's a subclavian artery stenosis.

395
00:17:29.970 --> 00:17:31.980
If you get a difference between the two arms,

396
00:17:31.980 --> 00:17:35.250
you think about a subclavian artery stenosis.

397
00:17:35.250 --> 00:17:38.490
Now usually these are asymptomatic.

398
00:17:38.490 --> 00:17:39.990
I actually only picked one up

399
00:17:39.990 --> 00:17:41.490
in the ER just serendipitously.

400
00:17:41.490 --> 00:17:43.560
My nurses were getting one bloods in one arm

401
00:17:43.560 --> 00:17:44.640
and then we took the cuff off

402
00:17:44.640 --> 00:17:45.840
and found the pressure in the other arm

403
00:17:45.840 --> 00:17:47.460
was completely different.

404
00:17:47.460 --> 00:17:50.160
And this patient actually was symptomatic,

405
00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:51.420
she came in saying, "I'm only here

406
00:17:51.420 --> 00:17:54.090
because I have some numbness or funny feeling, numbness,

407
00:17:54.090 --> 00:17:55.980
in my left upper extremity."

408
00:17:55.980 --> 00:17:57.660
And we had a significant difference.

409
00:17:57.660 --> 00:18:00.450
So typically the patients don't know it,

410
00:18:00.450 --> 00:18:02.520
until they start having some symptoms

411
00:18:02.520 --> 00:18:04.200
and you don't do anything about it

412
00:18:04.200 --> 00:18:06.690
until they start having symptoms,

413
00:18:06.690 --> 00:18:08.340
until they start having symptoms.

414
00:18:09.261 --> 00:18:11.130
Now moving downstream,

415
00:18:11.130 --> 00:18:14.100
okay, let's go back to our patient with claudication.

416
00:18:14.100 --> 00:18:16.410
How do you manage the patient with claudication?

417
00:18:16.410 --> 00:18:19.800
On the left hand side, because this patient you now know

418
00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:21.960
has some atherosclerotic disease,

419
00:18:21.960 --> 00:18:23.640
you're gonna do all the stuff on the left hand side

420
00:18:23.640 --> 00:18:25.200
that you normally would do anyway.

421
00:18:25.200 --> 00:18:27.660
This is just risk factor modification.

422
00:18:27.660 --> 00:18:30.180
This is like the no-brainer side of the slide.

423
00:18:30.180 --> 00:18:31.470
You are gonna tell them to stop smoking

424
00:18:31.470 --> 00:18:33.180
and you're gonna control their blood pressure and diabetes

425
00:18:33.180 --> 00:18:35.010
and you're gonna need to put them on aspirin or clopidogrel,

426
00:18:35.010 --> 00:18:38.010
just monotherapy, not dual antiplatelet therapy,

427
00:18:38.010 --> 00:18:39.443
you're gonna put them on something.

428
00:18:40.350 --> 00:18:43.290
What are the things the patient can do

429
00:18:43.290 --> 00:18:44.790
to help him or her

430
00:18:44.790 --> 00:18:49.620
walk longer, better, faster, without pain?

431
00:18:49.620 --> 00:18:51.390
That's the right hand side.

432
00:18:51.390 --> 00:18:54.450
So the answers to that is exercise, colostazol

433
00:18:54.450 --> 00:18:55.860
and lipid lowering agents.

434
00:18:55.860 --> 00:18:57.090
So it's been shown

435
00:18:57.090 --> 00:19:00.030
that if you have supervised exercise training,

436
00:19:00.030 --> 00:19:03.033
this will improve pain-free walking.

437
00:19:04.470 --> 00:19:05.550
So you know this,

438
00:19:05.550 --> 00:19:07.110
anytime they ask on the board if it's exercise,

439
00:19:07.110 --> 00:19:10.410
you just say yes, that's a good thing, that's easy.

440
00:19:10.410 --> 00:19:11.760
Lipid lowering agents have been shown

441
00:19:11.760 --> 00:19:13.320
to improve pain-free walking

442
00:19:13.320 --> 00:19:17.190
and drug therapy, the drug cilostazol, brand name Pletal,

443
00:19:17.190 --> 00:19:18.750
people don't really know how it works,

444
00:19:18.750 --> 00:19:20.700
actually we think it's a vasodilator,

445
00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:25.083
but has been shown to increase pain-free walking, also.

446
00:19:26.340 --> 00:19:30.210
So you have the patient who hopefully listened

447
00:19:30.210 --> 00:19:31.740
to everything you told them to do,

448
00:19:31.740 --> 00:19:34.440
they did exercise,

449
00:19:34.440 --> 00:19:38.490
they did their drug therapy and their symptoms improve,

450
00:19:38.490 --> 00:19:39.540
you do nothing.

451
00:19:39.540 --> 00:19:42.600
But if your patients like my patients',

452
00:19:42.600 --> 00:19:44.730
completely noncompliant, they're gonna keep smoking,

453
00:19:44.730 --> 00:19:45.630
they're not gonna take their drugs

454
00:19:45.630 --> 00:19:47.490
and they're not gonna exercise, what happens?

455
00:19:47.490 --> 00:19:50.820
Well then their symptoms will likely worsen.

456
00:19:50.820 --> 00:19:53.880
And what will happen is when their symptoms worsen,

457
00:19:53.880 --> 00:19:58.050
they're gonna go from stable angina legs to...

458
00:19:58.050 --> 00:20:00.030
unstable angina legs.

459
00:20:00.030 --> 00:20:01.680
It's just gonna keep getting worse

460
00:20:01.680 --> 00:20:04.260
and now they'll start having pain at rest.

461
00:20:04.260 --> 00:20:07.740
So when they start having pain at rest, what will they do?

462
00:20:07.740 --> 00:20:10.800
They'll don't like to keep their legs up now.

463
00:20:10.800 --> 00:20:11.940
Now they keep putting it down,

464
00:20:11.940 --> 00:20:13.290
hoping any blood will get down there.

465
00:20:13.290 --> 00:20:14.640
Their legs go down, what happens?

466
00:20:14.640 --> 00:20:16.410
They start getting edema of their legs,

467
00:20:16.410 --> 00:20:19.170
then they start having the hair loss and the shiny legs

468
00:20:19.170 --> 00:20:22.950
and the thickened nails and it'll go on and on and on

469
00:20:22.950 --> 00:20:26.220
and they get cyanosis, ulceration and ultimately gangrene,

470
00:20:26.220 --> 00:20:28.173
that's the the progression.

471
00:20:29.100 --> 00:20:30.720
I'm gonna digress for one slide,

472
00:20:30.720 --> 00:20:32.880
talk about lower extremity ulcers,

473
00:20:32.880 --> 00:20:34.830
just so we we're all on the same page,

474
00:20:34.830 --> 00:20:37.650
just in case you have a question on ulcers.

475
00:20:37.650 --> 00:20:40.290
This is a slide actually came from, "New England Journal,"

476
00:20:40.290 --> 00:20:41.640
really nice, just breaks up

477
00:20:41.640 --> 00:20:44.370
the four types of lower extremity ulcers,

478
00:20:44.370 --> 00:20:45.870
the venous ulcers, arterial ulcers,

479
00:20:45.870 --> 00:20:48.150
neuropathic or diabetic ulcers and pressure ulcers,

480
00:20:48.150 --> 00:20:49.110
the lower extremity.

481
00:20:49.110 --> 00:20:51.600
You've seen all these I'm sure in your practice.

482
00:20:51.600 --> 00:20:53.482
The venous ones, they're the first ones.

483
00:20:53.482 --> 00:20:55.680
Those are the very superficial ones

484
00:20:55.680 --> 00:20:58.074
that are often just above the medial malleolus,

485
00:20:58.074 --> 00:21:02.280
they're easily fryable, you touch them, they start bleeding,

486
00:21:02.280 --> 00:21:04.620
they have that brown-ey discoloration around them,

487
00:21:04.620 --> 00:21:05.490
you've seen the venous.

488
00:21:05.490 --> 00:21:09.930
The arterial on the other hand is when on your ankle or toe

489
00:21:09.930 --> 00:21:13.440
you get this hard thickened black eschar.

490
00:21:13.440 --> 00:21:15.960
You touch it, nothing bleeds 'cause it's arterial,

491
00:21:15.960 --> 00:21:17.430
there's no blood getting down there.

492
00:21:17.430 --> 00:21:20.760
Neuropathic is often over the bony prominences.

493
00:21:20.760 --> 00:21:21.810
You can see there the typical

494
00:21:21.810 --> 00:21:23.520
is the second metatarsal head.

495
00:21:23.520 --> 00:21:25.470
And then the pressure ulcers

496
00:21:25.470 --> 00:21:27.330
are also over those bony prominences

497
00:21:27.330 --> 00:21:31.380
that are resting on the bed, typically,

498
00:21:31.380 --> 00:21:33.183
on the heels and calcanei.

499
00:21:34.380 --> 00:21:36.655
Alright, we come back,

500
00:21:36.655 --> 00:21:40.530
back to our peripheral vascular disease.

501
00:21:40.530 --> 00:21:44.190
Should you screen all patients, asymptomatic patients,

502
00:21:44.190 --> 00:21:46.050
who are at risk with an ABI?

503
00:21:46.050 --> 00:21:48.828
So you have a 65-year-old comes into your office,

504
00:21:48.828 --> 00:21:51.030
he or she's a smoker,

505
00:21:51.030 --> 00:21:53.730
yes, you're gonna order up their AAA screen,

506
00:21:53.730 --> 00:21:56.670
but should you just do an ABI on them anyway?

507
00:21:56.670 --> 00:21:57.510
They're at risk

508
00:21:57.510 --> 00:22:00.210
and the answer to that question is we don't know.

509
00:22:00.210 --> 00:22:02.193
That's it, I from the USPSTF.

510
00:22:05.040 --> 00:22:07.507
Next question, let's turn the case scenario around.

511
00:22:07.507 --> 00:22:09.450
"A 72-year-old patient presents to the emergency department

512
00:22:09.450 --> 00:22:11.190
with sudden severe right leg pain,

513
00:22:11.190 --> 00:22:12.810
sudden severe right pain,

514
00:22:12.810 --> 00:22:14.430
located from the knees down to the toes.

515
00:22:14.430 --> 00:22:16.800
Past history seen for hypertension, diabetes.

516
00:22:16.800 --> 00:22:18.120
Vitals, the blood pressure's are good,

517
00:22:18.120 --> 00:22:20.850
but the pulse is elevated and irregular.

518
00:22:20.850 --> 00:22:23.250
She's afebrile, lungs are clear,

519
00:22:23.250 --> 00:22:25.410
her heart's rapidly, irregular, irregular.

520
00:22:25.410 --> 00:22:27.810
When you see in the boards, "Irregular, irregular,"

521
00:22:27.810 --> 00:22:32.340
your brain says AFib, so AFib right leg is cool to touch,

522
00:22:32.340 --> 00:22:36.210
pale and color and you can't get pulses down below.

523
00:22:36.210 --> 00:22:37.110
This is a problem.

524
00:22:38.490 --> 00:22:40.800
So at this point, you should, "Start heparin

525
00:22:40.800 --> 00:22:42.540
and immediately consult the vascular surgeon,

526
00:22:42.540 --> 00:22:44.580
B, immediately obtain an ultrasound at lower extremity,

527
00:22:44.580 --> 00:22:46.260
C, immediately obtain an echocardiogram,

528
00:22:46.260 --> 00:22:49.167
D, immediately obtain an abdominal aortic ultrasound."

529
00:22:57.120 --> 00:22:59.190
Good, so three quarters of you got it.

530
00:22:59.190 --> 00:23:02.550
Yeah, this is a thromboembolic phenomenon

531
00:23:02.550 --> 00:23:04.710
that happened from the AFib.

532
00:23:04.710 --> 00:23:06.270
It didn't go up to the brain and cause stroke,

533
00:23:06.270 --> 00:23:08.576
it decided that clot decided to go downtown and,

534
00:23:08.576 --> 00:23:09.409
(Dr. Dachs clicking)

535
00:23:09.409 --> 00:23:11.820
lodge in one of the lower extremities.

536
00:23:11.820 --> 00:23:13.860
So you start heparin immediately

537
00:23:13.860 --> 00:23:15.090
and call your vascular surgeon.

538
00:23:15.090 --> 00:23:18.270
These patients present with The 5 "P's,"

539
00:23:18.270 --> 00:23:21.120
Pain, pallor, parasthesia, pulselessness, paralysis,

540
00:23:21.120 --> 00:23:24.303
there's a six poichlosis, or a cold extremity.

541
00:23:25.950 --> 00:23:30.540
So, we're gonna talk a bit more about this stroke

542
00:23:30.540 --> 00:23:33.480
a little later, but patients with AFib,

543
00:23:33.480 --> 00:23:36.600
where do these emboli that originate

544
00:23:36.600 --> 00:23:38.400
typically in the atrium, where do they go?

545
00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:40.260
It's interesting, about two thirds of them

546
00:23:40.260 --> 00:23:42.660
go downstream into the lower extremities,

547
00:23:42.660 --> 00:23:45.150
about 20% or 25% go up to the brain,

548
00:23:45.150 --> 00:23:46.470
we'll talk about stroke.

549
00:23:46.470 --> 00:23:47.771
Sometimes they start to go up and

550
00:23:47.771 --> 00:23:49.437
(Dr. Dachs clicking) make a right or left hand turn

551
00:23:49.437 --> 00:23:50.850
out to the upper extremities

552
00:23:50.850 --> 00:23:52.952
or sometimes they start going downstream and

553
00:23:52.952 --> 00:23:53.785
(Dr. Dachs clicking)

554
00:23:53.785 --> 00:23:56.400
decide then to pop into the superior mesenteric artery

555
00:23:56.400 --> 00:24:00.720
and then you get these acute SMA occlusion

556
00:24:00.720 --> 00:24:03.780
and they get that and they infarct all their bowel

557
00:24:03.780 --> 00:24:05.460
and they have this in incredible pain

558
00:24:05.460 --> 00:24:07.443
out of proportion to physical findings.

559
00:24:10.777 --> 00:24:13.230
"76-year-old patient with a history of hypertension,

560
00:24:13.230 --> 00:24:15.570
hyperlipidemia and smoking."

561
00:24:15.570 --> 00:24:16.970
Yeah, you know this patient.

562
00:24:18.886 --> 00:24:21.697
He or she comes in with this painful toe.

563
00:24:21.697 --> 00:24:24.510
"No history of trauma, no history of Afib,

564
00:24:24.510 --> 00:24:26.403
the toes are dusky blue in color,

565
00:24:26.403 --> 00:24:31.110
but there's pulses in your posterior tib and dorsalis pedis.

566
00:24:31.110 --> 00:24:32.130
The most likely diagnosis,"

567
00:24:32.130 --> 00:24:34.260
your choices are gonna be acute gout,

568
00:24:34.260 --> 00:24:36.393
Raynaud's, cellulitis, blue toe.

569
00:24:41.190 --> 00:24:42.633
This is blue toe syndrome.

570
00:24:43.620 --> 00:24:45.450
When patients come in with painful blue toes,

571
00:24:45.450 --> 00:24:46.900
that's the blue toe syndrome.

572
00:24:48.210 --> 00:24:52.020
And what it is, is that those are patients at risk,

573
00:24:52.020 --> 00:24:54.990
like the patient I just talked about,

574
00:24:54.990 --> 00:24:59.010
what they have, their aorta, thoracic and abdominal aorta,

575
00:24:59.010 --> 00:25:02.910
is all gummed up with atherosclerotic plaque,

576
00:25:02.910 --> 00:25:04.290
it's this plaque all over.

577
00:25:04.290 --> 00:25:07.515
And what will happen is that little bits of the plaque,

578
00:25:07.515 --> 00:25:09.590
this cholesterol emboli will go,

579
00:25:09.590 --> 00:25:10.423
(Dr. Dachs clicking)

580
00:25:10.423 --> 00:25:12.690
shooting downstream and it'll go shooting down

581
00:25:12.690 --> 00:25:15.510
into one of the digital arteries to one of your toes

582
00:25:15.510 --> 00:25:19.863
and you'll end up infarcting portion or all of your toe.

583
00:25:21.016 --> 00:25:25.050
There's no test for it, you can't do a blood test for it,

584
00:25:25.050 --> 00:25:28.260
you can't do a CTA to figure it out or anything like that.

585
00:25:28.260 --> 00:25:29.700
It's a clinical diagnosis.

586
00:25:29.700 --> 00:25:31.260
What do you do about it?

587
00:25:31.260 --> 00:25:32.370
You don't put them on heparin,

588
00:25:32.370 --> 00:25:34.020
because it's not a blood clot,

589
00:25:34.020 --> 00:25:37.830
it's a cholesterol emboli, a plaque emboli.

590
00:25:37.830 --> 00:25:40.680
And so you literally treat it just like you treat frostbite,

591
00:25:40.680 --> 00:25:44.493
you see what lives, what dies and you go on from there.

592
00:25:46.170 --> 00:25:49.650
Last slide here, Raynaud's phenomenon.

593
00:25:49.650 --> 00:25:51.330
They don't want you to call it a disease anymore,

594
00:25:51.330 --> 00:25:52.710
it's a phenomenon.

595
00:25:52.710 --> 00:25:55.410
And you know what it is, that recurrent vasospasm

596
00:25:55.410 --> 00:26:00.410
of the fingers, toes, nose, in response to cold

597
00:26:01.020 --> 00:26:02.760
and oh, it's fascinating.

598
00:26:02.760 --> 00:26:05.187
3% to 5% of the population have it

599
00:26:05.187 --> 00:26:08.220
and it's primary or idiopathic, we don't know what do it.

600
00:26:08.220 --> 00:26:11.100
There's some people, it's due to underlying disease,

601
00:26:11.100 --> 00:26:13.263
such as scleroderma.

602
00:26:14.760 --> 00:26:17.659
And with that, I'm gonna say thank you very much!

603
00:26:17.659 --> 00:26:20.409
(relaxing music)

